04708nam a22007455i 9781442656314DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20161984onc    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1002265927  a(OCoLC)1004882930  a(OCoLC)1011452702  a(OCoLC)1013963076  a(OCoLC)999365970  a97814426563147 a10.3138/97814426563142doi  a(DE-B1597)465688  a(OCoLC)944178647  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aML1406b.A53 1984 7aMUS0070002bisacsh04a784/.09/042191 aAnhalt, Istvan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAlternative Voices :bEssays on Contemporary Vocal and Choral Composition /cIstvan Anhalt. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2016] 4c©1984  a1 online resource (346 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. Theme and recent background -- tPart one -- t2. Berio’s Sequenza III: A portrait -- t3. Ligeti’s Nouvelles Aventures: A small group as a model for composition -- t4. Lutosławski’s Trois Poèmes d’Henri Michaux: Voices of a multitude -- tPart two -- t5. Blurred boundaries -- t6. Deep themes, not so hidden -- t7. Orpheus resurgent... perhaps -- t8. Alternative voices -- tNotes -- tList of compositions -- tBibliography -- tIndex of names and titles -- tIndex of subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIstvan Anhalt, himself a composer of many vocal works, has written an interdisciplinary study of the innovative vocal and choral music that has emerged in Europe and North America since the Second World War. This music has amazed, confused, sometimes shocked, and often deeply moved its listeners, and the author probes its very roots. Anhalt sketches briefly the antecedents of this revolutionary music and then illustrates the subject by looking closely at works by three of the greatest composers of modern vocal and choral music: Luciano Berio’s Sequenza III for female solo voice, GyÓ§rgy Ligeti’s Nouvelles Aventures for three solo voices and small instrumental ensemble, and Witold Lutoslawski’s Trois Poèmes d’Henri Michaux for large chorus and orchestra. The author next seeks to formulate a conceptual framework to explain post-war vocal composition. He discusses relationships between poetry and music, speaking and singing, theatre and music, and composers and performers. He identifies and examines recurring themes in his corpus, including hallowed and cursed names, repetition as a mythical and/or mystical technique, the arcane, magical elements in music and language, and music as spectacle or celebration and as a search for the past. Anhalt also considers the structural elements and compositional procedures used in creating this type of music. The complex associations with other creative activities that typify modern vocal composition help to make it, as Anhalt shows clearly, an extraordinary rich mosaic of alternative voices.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aVocal musicy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aMUSIC / Instruction & Study / Composition.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144265631440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442656314423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442656314.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK